  "read": "The dot-K variant batches selected keys before routing them into active compressed groups: contrib[K,D] = grad_logits[:,K]^T @ q[:,D] + probs[:,K]^T @ grad_output[:,D], then route[active_group,K] @ contrib. It keeps the same materialized probs/grad_logits diagnostic contract as the scalar active-list probe. This is a strong S128/S512 accumulator-body improvement, but it is not a production S4096 layer-2 solution. At S512 layer2 it improves the accumulator from the scalar active-list 3.134 ms to 0.416 ms and beats the materialized PyTorch reference at 1.58 ms. At S4096 layer2, the active-group count is too high: 515.9 mean and 1024 max active groups per tile. The route dot becomes dense over hundreds of groups, so the best timing-only point is still 47.26-47.49 ms, far above the current query-major atomic slice. The next kernel must avoid dense active-group route matrices at the hard CR4/topk512 layer, likely by using sparse/segmented route accumulation inside the recompute tile or fusing LI/compressor gradients before dKV writes.",
